[6.6](https://docs.doxee.com/docs/en/process-designer-6-6)

[6.7](https://docs.doxee.com/docs/en/process-designer-6-7)

Data mode is used for extensive display and editing of mappings and any other information related to the handling of data within a process. It can be activated for an editor by clicking on the *Toggle Data Mode* button in the toolbar while the editor is active. Click on the same button again to return to the normal mode. It can be activated and deactivated for different editors independently. If no editor is open and active, the button disabled and grayed out. In data mode, the editor, the outline view and the properties view behave a bit differently. The exact differences in these components and how to use the additional features for editing mappings, is described in the following sub-sections.

## Editor
While in data mode, the basic editing possibilities for process components (adding, deleting, moving, resizing, etc.) are disabled. The basic structure of the process as well as the size and position of individual elements is fixed. Only the handling of mappings within the elements is possible. For this purpose, selecting a process element which can have mappings, opens a panel displaying the mappings for the element. Selecting multiple elements, opens this panel for each of them. For activities and tasks, in addition to the existing mappings of an element, there are also placeholders for the expected input and output parameters. The graphical elements and editing capabilities of the mapping field, the mappings and the parameter placeholders are described in the following sections.

![](data:image/png;base64,)*Figure 13. Mapping panel for a start element containing 3 mappings.*

![](data:image/png;base64,)*Figure 14. Mapping panel for an activity containing 2 input mappings, 6 input parameter placeholders, 1 output mapping and 3 output parameter placeholders.*

![](data:image/png;base64,)*Figure 15. Mapping panel for all elements in the example process.*

### Mapping Panel
The panel displaying the mappings replaces the standard graphical representation of a process element while it is selected. Its width is equal to the width of the element, the hight depends on the number and layout of the contained components, stretching down as far as required. The text line containing name or id is moved above the panel, while it is open.

For start, end and mapping elements the mappings and parameter placeholders are always displayed as a single column stretching the whole panel from left to right. For activities and tasks there are different layouts for separating input and output mappings. The default layout groups them into two columns, the left one for inputs, the right one for outputs. Due to the reduced horizontal space in this layout, their content is also shortened. Different layouts can be selected from the dropdown menu available next to the *Toggle Data Mode *button in the workbench toolbar. For each of them, input mappings exceed the border of the panel on the left side, output mappings exceed the border on the right.

Mappings can be added to the element in four ways:

- Add an empty mapping using the *Add* button in the context button pad appearing on the top right when hovering over the panel.

- Add a mapping with predefined variable source using a data drop operation (see [Drag and Drop](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-process-designer-process-designer-user-guide-data-mode-1#drag-and-drop)). Does not work for output mappings.

- Add a new mapping with values taken from a placeholder by double clicking on a placeholder element.

- Paste an existing mapping from the clipboard using the *Paste* entry in the context menu or the shortcut while the panel is selected.

### Mappings
Mappings are represented as blue rectangles. They come in three different variations: One is the complete version showing both source and target, separated by two lines forming an arrow. The other two are shortened versions for input and output mappings, where either source or target is omitted. Only the first source of the mapping is shown. It is represented by an icon at the beginning, indicating the source type and a text label showing the value. These are not visible in the shortened version of the input mapping. The target is only displayed in form of a text label containing the target name. This is not visible in the shortened version of the output mapping.

Selecting a mapping shows the available data connects for it. Data connections are arrows between mappings, which indicate that the variable created by the start mapping is used as a source in the end mapping. These connections are not part of the process definition file and cannot be created or deleted. They are an abstraction derived from the defined mappings and a pure visualization tool for tracking the usage and movement of data throughout the process.

The following modification options are available:

- Delete: Use the *Delete* button in the context button pad or press the delete key while the mapping is selected.

- Copy: Use the *Copy* entry in the context menu or the shortcut while the mapping is selected.

- Cut: Use the *Cut* entry in the context menu or the shortcut while the mapping is selected.

- Select target type: Click the *Target Type* button in the context button pad and select the type from the dropdown list.

- Select source type: Click the *Source Type* button in the context button pad and select the type from the dropdown list. The button shows the icon for the currently selected type.

- Switch required flag: Click the *Required* button in the context button pad. The icon on the button represents the current state.

- Change target variable name: Edit the name in the small text field which appears when clicking on the target name label while the mapping is selected. Apply the new value by pressing the return key or cancel by pressing the escape key. Only available if the target name label is visible. Can also be achieved using a drag operation (see [Drag and Drop](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-process-designer-process-designer-user-guide-data-mode-1#drag-and-drop)).

- Change source value: Edit the value in the small text field which appears when clicking on the source value label while the mapping is selected. Apply the new value by pressing the return key or cancel by pressing the escape key. Only available if the source value label is visible. Can also be achieved using a drop operation (see [Drag and Drop](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-process-designer-process-designer-user-guide-data-mode-1#drag-and-drop)).

### Parameter Placeholders
The parameter placeholders are shown as light blue, rounded rectangles and are available for activities and tasks. They show the parameter variables for inputs and outputs and offer a simple way to create mappings providing these variables. The text label shows the parameter name. A placeholder with a red border indicates that the parameter is required by the activity/task. Create a mapping from the placeholder by double clicking it.

The placeholders belonging to the input column show which variables an activity/task expects to find in its local pipeline. The parameter name is used as the target name of a created mapping.

The placeholders belonging to the output column show which variables are written back to the local pipeline and provided for mapping to the process by an activity/task. The parameter name is used as the source value for the variable source of a created mapping.

Placeholders can also be used in drag and drop operations (see [Drag and Drop](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-process-designer-process-designer-user-guide-data-mode-1#drag-and-drop)).

### Conditions
Because the conditions of a decision element can access pipeline variables, there is also a graphical representation of conditions in the editor in data mode. When a decision element is selected in data mode, a panel like the one used for mappings is opened. Instead of the mapping boxes it contains conditions represented by rounded, orange elements with the condition text displayed inside. When a condition is selected and it uses variables from the pipeline, incoming data connections are shown.

## Outline
In data mode the outline contains a list of elements called *Variables*. Each of these elements represents a variable which can potentially exist in the main pipeline during runtime. The shown variables depend on the slection in the editor. If a Process Element ist selected, only the variables which can exist at this point in the process are shown in the outline. If no Process Element is selected, all variables which can exist in the main process pipeline are shown.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)*Figure 16. Outline view in data mode.*

When a variable is selected in the outline, all related mappings are highlighted in the editor. Mappings which create or modify the variable are shown with a green background, mappings which use the variable as a source are shown with a yellow background. Using the *Edit* entry in the context menu of the *Vriable* element opens a dialog for changing the name of the variable. This updates all references to this variable, meaning that all the target names and source values where it is used are changed.

In addition to the variables, the outline also shows the process constants in the same way they are shown when data mode is not active. While in data mode the constants can be used in the same way as variables.

## Properties
In data mode the *General* tab is not visible. The *Data* tab provides some additional drag and drop features for interacting with the editor and outline.

## Drag and Drop
Data mode enables many different drag and drop operations within and between the editor, outline and properties view. The available operations for different combinations of dragged and dropped elements are listed and described below.

**From mapping to mapping**

Sets the target variable of the dragged mapping as variable source of the dropped upon mapping. If the ctrl is pressed while dropping, it adds a source instead of overwriting the first one. This works within the editor and also in both directions between editor and properties view. For input and output mappings in the editor, it is only possible to drop an output onto an input.

**From mapping to mapping panel**

A dragged mapping can also be dropped onto the mapping panel of a selected process element. This creates a new mapping in the dropped panel with the target variable of the dragged mapping as variable source. When dropping on an activity/task, this always creates an input mapping.

**From mapping to parameter placeholder**

Dropping a mapping onto an input placeholder in the editor or properties view, creates a new mapping with the target variable of the dragged mapping as variable source and the parameter as target variable. Not available for output placeholders.

**From mapping to outline variable**

Sets the target variable name of the dragged mapping to the name of the dropped upon variable.

**From parameter placeholder to mapping**

Dropping an output placeholder onto a mapping creates a new mapping for the placeholder and sets the target variable of this new mapping as variable source of the dropped upon mapping. If the ctrl is pressed while dropping, it adds a source instead of overwriting the first one. Not available for input placeholders.

**From parameter placeholder to mapping panel**

Dropping an output placeholder onto a mapping panel creates a new mapping for the placeholder and another new mapping in the dropped panel with the target variable of the new output mapping as variable source. Not available for input placeholders.

**From parameter placeholder to parameter placeholder**

Dragging an output placeholder onto an input placeholder creates a new mapping for both placeholders. The target variable of the new output mapping is set as variable source of the new input mapping. Not available the other way around.

**From parameter placeholder to outline variable**

Dropping an output placeholder onto a variable in the outline, creates a new mapping for the placeholder and sets the dropped upon variable as target variable. Not available for input placeholders.

**From outline variable to mapping**

Sets the dragged variable as variable source of the mapping. If the ctrl is pressed while dropping, it adds a source instead of overwriting the first one.

**From outline variable to mapping panel**

Creates a new mapping with the dragged variable as variable source.

**From outline variable to parameter placeholder**

Dropping a variable onto an input placeholder creates a new mapping for the placeholder with the dragged variable as variable source. Not available for output placeholders.
